## 7. KafkaPrincipal Extraction

**Key files:**
- `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/authenticator/DefaultKafkaPrincipalBuilder.java`
- `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/auth/KafkaPrincipal.java`
- `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/security/auth/SaslAuthenticationContext.java`

### Build Path

After `saslServer.isComplete()` transitions the state to `COMPLETE`, `KafkaChannel.principal()` calls `SaslServerAuthenticator.principal()`:

```java
public KafkaPrincipal principal() {
    Optional<SSLSession> sslSession = transportLayer instanceof SslTransportLayer ?
            Optional.of(((SslTransportLayer) transportLayer).sslSession()) : Optional.empty();
    SaslAuthenticationContext context = new SaslAuthenticationContext(
            saslServer, securityProtocol, clientAddress(), listenerName.value(), sslSession);
    KafkaPrincipal principal = principalBuilder.build(context);
    if (ScramMechanism.isScram(saslMechanism) &&
            Boolean.parseBoolean((String) saslServer.getNegotiatedProperty(ScramLoginModule.TOKEN_AUTH_CONFIG))) {
        principal.tokenAuthenticated(true);
    }
    return principal;
}
```

The `SaslAuthenticationContext` carries the live `SaslServer` instance, giving custom `KafkaPrincipalBuilder` implementations access to all negotiated properties (e.g., the full `OAuthBearerToken` for claim-based authorization).

### DefaultKafkaPrincipalBuilder.build()

```java
} else if (context instanceof SaslAuthenticationContext) {
    SaslServer saslServer = ((SaslAuthenticationContext) context).server();
    if (SaslConfigs.GSSAPI_MECHANISM.equals(saslServer.getMechanismName()))
        return applyKerberosShortNamer(saslServer.getAuthorizationID());
    else
        return new KafkaPrincipal(KafkaPrincipal.USER_TYPE, saslServer.getAuthorizationID());
}
```

For all non-GSSAPI SASL mechanisms, the principal is `User:<authorizationId>` where `authorizationId` is:

| Mechanism    | Source of authorizationId                                 |
|--------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|
| PLAIN        | `authcid` (username extracted from NUL-delimited payload) |
| SCRAM        | `username` (or token owner if delegation token)           |
| OAUTHBEARER  | `token.principalName()` (claim from JWT)                  |
| GSSAPI       | `authenticationID` after Kerberos short-name mapping      |

For PLAINTEXT connections, `build()` returns `KafkaPrincipal.ANONYMOUS` (`User:ANONYMOUS`).

### KafkaPrincipal Equality

```java
public boolean equals(Object o) {
    // ...
    return principalType.equals(that.principalType) && name.equals(that.name);
}
```

Equality is based on `(principalType, name)` only. `tokenAuthenticated` is **not** part of equality. Two principals with the same type and name compare equal regardless of whether one was authenticated via a delegation token. The `tokenAuthenticated` flag is used for auditing and downstream checks (e.g., restricting operations to token-authenticated sessions) but cannot be relied on for ACL comparison.

### KafkaPrincipal Transport (Inter-Broker)

`DefaultKafkaPrincipalBuilder` also implements `KafkaPrincipalSerde`:

```java
public byte[] serialize(KafkaPrincipal principal) {
    DefaultPrincipalData data = new DefaultPrincipalData()
        .setType(principal.getPrincipalType())
        .setName(principal.getName())
        .setTokenAuthenticated(principal.tokenAuthenticated());
    return MessageUtil.toVersionPrefixedBytes(DefaultPrincipalData.HIGHEST_SUPPORTED_VERSION, data);
}
```

When `KafkaPrincipal` is forwarded between brokers (e.g., for consumer group coordination), it is serialized and deserialized. The deserializer validates the version field against `LOWEST_SUPPORTED_VERSION` and `HIGHEST_SUPPORTED_VERSION`, throwing `SerializationException` on out-of-range values.

